{"name":"Courtesy","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>With this skill, the character knows how to navigate the murky and treacherous waters of life amongst the Nobility. He understands the subtleties and extravagances of courtly behaviour, and can use them to his own advantage.With this skill, the character knows how to navigate the murky and treacherous waters of life amongst the Nobility. He understands the subtleties and extravagances of courtly behaviour, and can use them to his own advantage.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"1KYhpHJY9KU5auQ4"}
{"name":"Tracking","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>With this skill a character can locate the tracks of a specific creature and follow them. A test must be made to locate the trail and then again once every ten minutes they are being followed. Penalties or bonuses may apply depending on how long it was since the tracks were made, what the ground is like, what the weather conditions have been since the tracks were made, etc.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Con","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"1sfiUMuUkYikAEqI"}
{"name":"Elemental Casting (Earth)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill used for casting Alchemical spells. Each of the four Elements is a separate skill. See the Alchemy chapter for more details.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":0},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"2EFhlttuBQiqDFMY"}
{"name":"Culture(Other)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>Each Culture skill is used to provide information about the common world view of that group of people (or creatures). This includes history, politics, weather cycles, geography, superstitions and popular mythology. A character who is very well- travelled may have Culture (France), Culture (India), etc.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"3L0luIR7h4aIpxXu"}
{"name":"Streetwise","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>Streetwise allows a character to find black markets, fences for stolen goods, and general information. Such uses of Streetwise normally require a minimum of 1D4 hours.</p>","base1":"Pow","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"5RCg4kueN8oJ8SVG"}
{"name":"Elemental Casting (Fire)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill used for casting Alchemical spells. Each of the four Elements is a separate skill. See the Alchemy chapter for more details.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"6Rm38WbVIkItteYB"}
{"name":"Elemental Casting (Water)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill used for casting Alchemical spells. Each of the four Elements is a separate skill. See the Alchemy chapter for more details.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":0},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"6r4XuJ1tsrk4Ol2V"}
{"name":"Ranged Combat (Bow)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to use longbows and short bows, which take more training than crossbows.</p>\n<p>Ranged Combat (Bows) skill begins at the same level as the character&rsquo;s common Ranged Combat skill. So a character with a Ranged Combat skill of 56% can buy Ranged Combat (Bows) at 56%.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Dex","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"9IR9BWMmmN2W9bMB"}
{"name":"Healing (Type)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill to heal major wounds, cure diseases, alleviate the effects of poisons, and the like. Use of this skill will always require the correct healer&rsquo;s kit. Each use of the Healing skill generally takes 1D4+1 minutes to perform.</p>\n<p>There are three types of Healing: Galenic, Herbal, and Paracelsan. A healer must have the correct healing kit for the type of healing in which he is trained. Lack of a healing kit imposes -25% penalty on the skill roll; use of a healing kit from a different Healing type imposes a -50% penalty on the skill roll &ndash; it's very easy to&nbsp; poison your patient if you don't know what your ingredients are!</p>\n<p>Galenic Healing: This is the &ldquo;respectable&rdquo; form of healing, as taught in universities. Galenic Physicians tend to administer to the upper classes and use a mixture of bleeding (usually with leeches), changes in diet to &ldquo;balance the humours&rdquo; and astrology.</p>\n<p>Herbal Healing: Herbalists use natural ingredients such as herbs, barks, teas, tinctures and poultices to perform their healing. They are usually found in country districts and are often accused of witchcraft. It may even be true!</p>\n<p>Paracelsan Healing: Paracelsan Physicians follow the teachings of the 16th century physician Paracelsus, who came up with a new system of medicine using chemicals, especially mercury, salt and sulphur. He was very much a &ldquo;people's physician&rdquo; and modern Paracelsans tend to be found among the lower orders, where they heal the poor for a much smaller fee than the Galenic healers.</p>\n<p>Curing Diseases: A successful Healing test allows a patient under the effect of a disease to add a bonus, equal to the healer&rsquo;s Healing divided by 10 (the critical success range) to his next opposed Resilience versus Potency test to resist the disease.</p>\n<p>Curing Poisons: A successful Healing test allows a patient under the effect of a poison to attempt a second opposed Resilience versus Potency test, with the patient gaining a bonus to his Resilience test equal to the healer&rsquo;s Healing divided by 10 (the critical success range).</p>\n<p>First Aid: If a character&rsquo;s Healing skill is higher than her First Aid skill, she may use this skill instead of First Aid to perform the tasks that First Aid can do.</p>\n<p>Serious Wound: A successful Healing roll will restore 1D6 Hit Points and remove the effects of a Serious Wound even if Hit Points are not up to their maximum.</p>\n<p>Grave Wound: A successful Healing roll will restore Hit Points to 0 and then add another 1D6 Hit Points. However, injuries suffered from a Grave Wound are&nbsp; permanent, and no amount of healing will restore lost Attributes.</p>","base1":"Str","base2":"Str","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"CRNHi4JtZCkISePN"}
{"name":"Alchemy","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill of making Philosopher&rsquo;s Stones and potions in the laboratory. Its use is described in detail in the Alchemy chapter.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"EC4JOQJIN67HVL9E"}
{"name":"Oratory","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill is used when addressing large groups of people, such as a priest&nbsp; addressing the faithful or a general exhorting his troops to victory on the eve of a battle. In effect, it is much like Influence, save that it relies more upon emotional appeal than intellectual stimulation and is used for larger groups of people. If the orator&rsquo;s appeal is on behalf of his Faction, Righteousness is used instead (see the Factions chapter).</p>","base1":"Pow","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"EHfuuHBOCYKrrfxt"}
{"name":"Commerce","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill is primarily used when characters trade, barter or other wise negotiate over the sale of goods. Such transactions require an Opposed Test using the Commerce of the buyer versus the Commerce of the seller. If the buyer wins he or she gets a discount of -10% for a success and -25% for a critical. If the seller wins the price that they can sell the item for increases of +10% for a success and +25% for a critical. If a character fumbles their roll double the increase or decrease accordingly.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Hd53TdVviKA60eP6"}
{"name":"Beliefs","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill provides knowledge of the Beliefs of a particular Faction. It also gives the character information about important members of that Faction,&nbsp; where to find members of that Faction when visiting new places, etc. Knowledge of each individual Faction&rsquo;s beliefs and organisational structure constitutes a separate skill (e.g., Beliefs (Catholic) is a completely different skill to Beliefs (Guild), and&nbsp; so on). Adventurers begin play with the Beliefs skill pertaining to their own Faction, but can learn the Beliefs of other Factions by observation, discussion and research.</p>\n<p>A character who does not belong to a Faction can attempt to pass himself off as a member of that Faction with an opposed test of his Beliefs (Faction) against the Righteousness of the Faction member. A success means that the Faction member is fooled and accepts the character as a fellow member. The skill can also be used to make sure a character knows the right rituals and sayings in a church service of another Faction.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"KExyRWzBx25DlYLh"}
{"name":"Shiphandling","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill is used in the same way as Boating but is instead applied to larger waterborne craft that are driven by sail or rows of oars.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Con","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"L5YpB4Mdi7HETvSi"}
{"name":"Witchcraft","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>The Witchcraft skill reflects the knowledge of all the spells learned by a Witch. Its use is described in detail in the Witchcraft chapter.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":0},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"OLss8jK2gBCoTLtn"}
{"name":"Elemental Casting (Air)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the skill used for casting Alchemical spells. Each of the four Elements is a separate skill. See the Alchemy chapter for more details.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":0},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"PpICqnoGMlZMHY2P"}
{"name":"Play Instrument (Type)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>The Play Instrument skill is actually several separate skills grouped under a single heading. Play Instrument (Dulcimer), Play Instrument (Flute) and Play Instrument (Spoons) are all individual skills. A successful test with this skill will result in the audience being pleased by the character&rsquo;s performance.</p>","base1":"Dex","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"RLstVHNG5GYjjy1K"}
{"name":"Craft(Type)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>The Craft skill is actually several separate skills grouped under a single heading. Craft (Armourer), Craft (Carpenter) and Craft (Potter) are all individual skills. The following list is by no means exhaustive: Apothecary, armourer, baker,&nbsp; basketweaver, blacksmith, bowyer, brewer, butcher, candlemaker, carpenter, cartographer, cobbler, cooper, fletcher, joiner, leatherworker, mason, painter,&nbsp; potter, sculptor, smith, tailor, weaponsmith, weaver.</p>","base1":"Dex","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"RnNBwcMMNfT2NjK9"}
{"name":"Seduction","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to use a mixture of sex appeal and flirting in order to win over&nbsp; another individual and persuade them to do something that they might not otherwise do. Seduction is opposed either by Persistence or Righteousness,&nbsp; depending on the nature of the task required by the seducer and the Faction of the seduced. If successful, the target will perform one task or action. Penalties may be applied to the Seduction roll if the required action is against the best interests or morality of the character being seduced.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"SzUZ88lGNFLpBpMC"}
{"name":"Teaching","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to impart new skills to, or improve the existing skills of, another character. For more information, see Adventurer Improvement.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"ZCcQFKUy2APhL8bW"}
{"name":"Lore (Type)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>Lore is actually a number of separate skills. It represents theoretical knowledge of a subject, rather than practical ability. So Lore (Art) gives knowledge of the history of art, well-known painters, etc., but Art (Painting) skill is needed to actually create a painting. The Advanced range of possibilities for this skill is limited only by a player&rsquo;s imagination but a list of potential areas of Lore study are listed here:</p>\n<p>animals, art, astronomy, gambling, geography, heraldry, law, logistics, military tactics, minerals, philosophy, poisons, plants, regional, theology.</p>\n<p>Some particular Lore skills have specific game effects:</p>\n<p>Aristotelian Science: This is knowledge of the scientific theories behind the workings of alchemy. On a successful roll, a character with this skill can use it to identify spells cast by Alchemists, even if he lacks the ability to cast spells himself.</p>\n<p>Research: This is the ability to find out about a particular topic by doing research in a library or collection of books, newspapers, scientific papers, etc. The&nbsp; difficulty of the task will depend on the quality of the library and the amount of time taken.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Zax64FBwMcWukxrh"}
{"name":"Gambling","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to take part in games of chance and understand the rules, the odds of winning and the like, whether the game be cards, cock-fighting, billiards or horse-racing. A successful roll will tell if opponents are cheating, if the horse has been nobbled, etc. A critical success means the character will win even if the opponents are cheating, while a fumble means the character has lost very badly indeed.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Pow","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"b2Moju74NEPmzuTP"}
{"name":"Dual Weapons (Weapon & Weapon)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to use two weapons at the same time without any penalty for using the off-hand. The character does not get any extra attacks in the round, but can choose which weapon he uses in any particular round. If performing an All Out Attack, a character with one these skills can make two attacks without the normal penalty.</p>\n<p>Note: Each pair of weapons is a separate skill, and Dual Weapons skill can never be higher than the lowest of the two weapons. For instance, a character with Close Combat 75% and Gun Combat 62% cannot have Dual Weapons (Sword and Pistol) higher than 62%. In order to raise Dual Weapons skill, he would first have to raise Gun Combat skill</p>\n<p>Common techniques include:</p>\n<p>Sword and Pistol: the Adventurer begins combat with a pistol in one hand and a sword in the other. The sword can be used in close combat, and the pistol kept as a threat or the pistol can be fired first, before the enemy reaches close combat&nbsp; r ange. Once the pistol has been fired, it is usually tucked into the belt, or just discarded if the fight is pressing. This technique can be useful when on foot and facing a mounted foe &ndash; the standard method is to shoot the horse and then stab the rider when he falls off!</p>\n<p>Sword and Main Gauche: If performing an All Out Defence, a character can parry twice without the normal penalty. Some Main Gauche weapons also allow bonuses to certain close combat actions such as Disarming Attack &ndash; see weapon descriptions for details.</p>\n<p>Two Pistols: A character who has loaded two guns before combat begins can fire both without the usual time out for reloading, and with this skill does not suffer a penalty for using a gun in his off-hand.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Dex","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"efDslrqOsa0hLdr5"}
{"name":"Disguise","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill is used to change a character&rsquo;s appearance and adopt a different outward persona. It is usually opposed by a Perception test if one is trying to avoid being identified.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"f3RdNblygJisZ2a4"}
{"name":"Artillery","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill covers the loading, aiming and firing of cannon, mortars and other such non-portable black powder weapons. It also covers the making of grenades and powder bombs, and the proper storage and maintenance of such weapons.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Dex","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"jv926hoiRn6UvaPx"}
{"name":"Art","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill allows a character to create works of art. Like the Lore and Craft skills, it is actually a large number of skills grouped together under one heading. Examples include (but are not limited to): Calligraphy, landscape gardening, musical composition, painting, sculpture, stained-glass, topiary, poetry, prose writing.</p>","base1":"Pow","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"nD77WAnbuNk0LwqD"}
{"name":"Language (Other)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>The Language skill is actually several separate skills grouped under a single heading. Language (English),&nbsp; language (German) and Language (French) are all individual skills.</p>\n<p>Every character with a Language skill of 50% or more is fluent in that language, though they will likely bear an accent if it is not their native language.</p>\n<p>A score in a Language skill of 80% or more will mean the character can also read and write in that language.</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Cha","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"pNyDuO4izTbkNtaY"}
{"name":"Close Combat (Polearms)","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to use such weapons as pikes, pollaxes, halberds, and the like in close combat.</p>\n<p>Close Combat (Polearms) skill begins at the same level as the character&rsquo;s common Close Combat skill. So a character with a Close Combat skill of 56% can buy Close Combat (Polearms) at 56%.</p>","base1":"Str","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"rRHu8FPOMGciwNmD"}
{"name":"Survivial","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>One Survival test will be required every day that a character lacks food, water or a safe place to sleep. Success indicates the character manages to find whatever he is lacking &ndash; failure means he will go without which, over several days, could result in very serious consequences. Survival tests are not used when the character is in a city or town.</p>","base1":"Pow","base2":"Con","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"rnMWYDOs7K3Q1Odt"}
{"name":"Engineering","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This skill is used to design, build, activate, repair, sabotage or disassemble large mechanisms or constructs such as siege machines, city gates and drawbridges, mineshafts, sailing ships and so forth</p>","base1":"Int","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"uKKWUxiDoPoRFk4t"}
{"name":"Mechanisms","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This is the ability to use and repair mechanical devices. It can also be used to pick locks with appropriate lock-picking tools.</p>\n<p>Picking a lock or disassembling a trap usually takes at least one minute (12 Combat Rounds) to perform, while larger devices will take longer.</p>\n<p>Usually, a character will simply make a Mechanisms test in order to succeed at assembling or disassembling a device, with appropriate bonuses or penalties decided upon by the Games Master. If a device has been designed to specifically resist attempts at disassembly, the Mechanisms test becomes opposed by the Mechanisms skill of the character who created it.</p>","base1":"Dex","base2":"Int","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"w1NbsmpF5IvYRyTk"}
{"name":"Boating","permission":{"default":0,"5OXcsyHbucZmXIwZ":3},"type":"skill","data":{"description":"<p>This covers small waterborne craft propelled manually by oars or sometimes paddles. Travelling across calm water does not usually require a test but adverse conditions such as currents and weather can bestow penalties.</p>","base1":"Str","base2":"Con","baseSkill":"0","value":null},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"wSLx4c7a3xKW8Ty2"}
